data.content:
Here's the complete migration analysis and rewritten code for .NET 8.

## Inventory

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop` | Control flow for cleanup |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop` | Prevent rethrow so `finally` runs |
| `volatile bool _running` | Field | Primitive cancellation flag |

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown, so your catch block and `ResetAbort()` are dead code. If `GetNextItem()` blocks, `_running = false` alone will never stop the thread.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);       // pass token for checkpoint checks
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop gracefully
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If thread is STILL alive, it's stuck in uncooperative code.
        // There is no .NET 8 equivalent of Abort(). Log and move on —
        // IsBackground = true means it won't block process exit.
        if (_workerThread?.IsAlive == true)
        {
            // Log: "Worker thread did not exit within timeout"
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitHandle`, async I/O) — a bool cannot interrupt a blocked call |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative cancellation; code must check the token voluntarily |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids catching unrelated OCEs from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No auto-rethrow behavior exists; just exit the loop |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then Abort | `_workerThread.Join(timeout)` | Blocks until thread exits **or** timeout; no force-kill |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` holds timers/callbacks that must be disposed |

## Critical: You Must Update `GetNextItem`

The biggest pitfall — if `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection`, socket, or `WaitHandle`), cancellation **will not interrupt it** unless you pass the token through:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks forever, can't be cancelled
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until item available
}

// AFTER: wakes up when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If you're using `Thread.Sleep` inside `GetNextItem`:

```csharp
// BEFORE
Thread.Sleep(1000);

// AFTER — wakes immediately on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000);
```

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Token not passed through the full call chain** — If `ProcessItem` calls sub-methods that block, pass the token all the way down. One missing link and cancellation stalls.

2. **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** — Only catch it at this top-level loop. Let it propagate from inner methods.

3. **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — Leaks timer handles and registered callbacks.

4. **Expecting immediate cancellation** — Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations inside `ProcessItem`.

5. **Truly uncooperative code** — If `GetNextItem` calls third-party code you can't modify to accept a token, the only .NET 8 escape hatch is moving that work to a **child process** and using `Process.Kill()`.
